        "content": "[\n  \"Strategy 1: Move the existing activity 'send legitimation & custody account documents' so that it is executed immediately after the first exclusive block and before 'conduct risk disclosure'. Remove it from the 'data.customer.status == \\\"new\\\"' branch. This makes the sending of 'custody_account_contract' part of the common continuation after 'conclude custody account'. R1, R4, R6, and R7 are preserved because the customer-data flow, investment-advice resource, custody-account ordering, and update-customer-data behavior remain unchanged. Note: this may cause the documents to be sent also for existing customers, so it is valid only if that is acceptable.\",\n  \"Strategy 2: Keep the current new-customer branch unchanged and add a corresponding send activity to the non-new-customer branch after 'update customer data', for example 'send existing custody account documents' with send/write data object 'custody_account_contract'. This resolves the violation by ensuring that the exclusive structure contains a custody-account-contract sending activity in all branches. R1, R4, R6, and R7 are preserved. This is localized but may introduce document sending for existing customers.\",\n  \"Strategy 3: Add the send/write of 'custody_account_contract' to an existing common activity after the first exclusive block, preferably by extending 'conduct risk disclosure' so that it also sends or produces 'custody_account_contract'. This avoids adding a new activity and guarantees that after 'conclude custody account' the required data object is eventually sent. R1 is preserved as long as 'conduct risk disclosure' still receives customer data before execution; R4, R6, and R7 are unaffected. This is structurally minimal but may be semantically weaker if risk disclosure is not an appropriate activity for sending custody-account documents.\",\n  \"Strategy 4: Replace the current placement of 'send legitimation & custody account documents' with a post-exclusive conditional block: after the first exclusive block, insert an exclusive block with one branch conditioned on 'data.customer.status == \\\"new\\\"' containing 'send legitimation & custody account documents' that sends 'custody_account_contract', and another branch conditioned on 'not data.customer.status == \\\"new\\\"' that is empty. Remove the original send activity from the new-customer branch. This preserves behavior for existing customers while ensuring that whenever 'conclude custody account' occurs, the send activity eventually follows. R1, R4, R6, and R7 are preserved. If the compliance checker is path-insensitive and requires the send activity in every exclusive branch syntactically, this may only be a partial mitigation.\",\n  \"Strategy 5: If the compliance checker strictly requires all branches of the first exclusive block to contain both the triggering context and the send target, duplicate the custody-account conclusion flow in the non-new-customer branch by inserting, before 'update customer data', 'conduct customer identification & legitimation', then 'conclude custody account' executed by 'customer advisor', followed by a send activity for 'custody_account_contract'. This satisfies the leads-to relation structurally and preserves R6 by ensuring legitimation precedes conclusion. However, it significantly changes the process for existing customers and should only be used if re-concluding custody accounts for existing customers is business-valid.\"\n]",
